{
  "doc_id": "60238",
  "text": "Although several recent models mention links between domain-general and domainspecific systems [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , the model put forward in Figure 4 , which is adapted from the 'controlled semantic cognition' framework [CITATION_3] , differs from these models in at least two important aspects. First, recent models have a dual-route structure [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] , which separate a fast and efficient route from a slower and more controlled route. Although dual-route structures have gained prominence in social cognition recently, such as in the domain of theory of mind [CITATION_6] , the same data can be explained with a single route structure [CITATION_7] . Therefore, the model proposed in Figure 4 has a single route structure, which always has a degree of representation and control. The amount and type of information represented and the degree of control exerted will vary based on context. In some contexts, there will be minimal control, whereas in other contexts, there will be greater control exerted. But in all cases, as outlined in semantic cognition [CITATION_8] , imitative control will involve the same interacting systems of representation and control.",
